                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.112 B61/17.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Mexican Chargé d’Affaires</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-04-07">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 7, 1911</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 478.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to previous correspondence, and
                    particularly to the embassy’s note of the 17th ultimo, wherein it was stated
                    that the Mexican Government was conducting a thorough investigation to determine
                    the sovereignty of the territory on which Messrs. Converse and Blatt were
                    captured, I have the honor to say that the Department has not yet been advised
                    of the results of that investigation, and because of the urgency of the matter
                    would much appreciate the receipt of such advice at an early day.</p>
                <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson</hi>
                    </signed>
                    <lb/>(For <signed>Mr. Knox</signed>).</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
